WEBVTT

00:01.084 --> 00:03.795
<i>Previously on "The Rookie"...</i>
I'm gonna give you my car.

00:03.795 --> 00:05.047
What's the catch?
You have to keep checking in

00:05.047 --> 00:05.964
with me until you're off
the street, or no deal.

00:05.964 --> 00:08.509
‐Thanks.
‐Hey!

00:08.509 --> 00:10.636
I am hereby placing you
under administrative leave.

00:10.636 --> 00:12.137
Gun and badge.

00:12.137 --> 00:13.764
Guys like Doug Stanton
should not be training

00:13.764 --> 00:14.890
our next generation.

00:14.890 --> 00:16.099
If you had
your college degree,

00:16.099 --> 00:18.435
you would be able to be T. O.
in two years.

00:18.435 --> 00:19.353
Looks like
I'm going back to school.

00:19.353 --> 00:23.023
♪♪

00:23.023 --> 00:25.192
Thanks for letting me
do my laundry here.

00:25.192 --> 00:27.903
I swear my cousin's dryer
is possessed.

00:27.903 --> 00:29.404
Any time.

00:29.404 --> 00:31.323
Plus, it means I get to
make sure

00:31.323 --> 00:34.368
you have <i>a</i> vegetable
this month.

00:34.368 --> 00:36.703
I told you ‐‐ all the cool kids
are getting scurvy.

00:36.703 --> 00:38.163
Mm‐hmm.
Listen ‐‐

00:38.163 --> 00:39.873
I have to write a paper
for school

00:39.873 --> 00:42.042
about gender roles
in the workplace,

00:42.042 --> 00:43.585
and I'm supposed to
interview someone

00:43.585 --> 00:46.129
who's working a job that was
traditionally considered male.

00:46.129 --> 00:50.759
And you want to
interview...me?

00:50.759 --> 00:51.843
If you're not busy.

00:51.843 --> 00:53.887
I would be honored.

00:53.887 --> 00:55.722
If you're gonna make this weird,
I'll just ask someone else.

00:55.722 --> 00:57.391
No! I'm in.
We can ‐‐

00:57.391 --> 00:58.558
We can do it after dinner
tonight.

00:58.558 --> 01:00.602
I still have to get
the questions together.

01:00.602 --> 01:02.354
Okay. Well, how about
tomorrow night?

01:02.354 --> 01:04.106
I could pick you up
after my shift?

01:04.106 --> 01:06.358
I should be done on time
for once.

01:06.358 --> 01:08.860
My sergeant has us doing
site security

01:08.860 --> 01:10.487
for the CCOA convention.

01:10.487 --> 01:13.824
It's the California Covert
Operators Association.

01:13.824 --> 01:15.784
Undercover cops
have a convention?
[ Door opens ]

01:15.784 --> 01:17.953
Yeah. At a hotel,
if you can believe it.

01:17.953 --> 01:20.539
And it's advertised
on their website, so...

01:20.539 --> 01:22.499
Well, sounds like
the opposite of covert.

01:22.499 --> 01:23.834
Yeah, that's what I said.

01:23.834 --> 01:26.461
But I guess it's a space for
them to share trade secrets.

01:26.461 --> 01:28.130
And party
on the city's dime.

01:28.130 --> 01:29.881
While we make sure no bad guys
get close enough

01:29.881 --> 01:31.258
to ID an undercover cop.

01:31.258 --> 01:32.759
Well, sadly,
I'll be missing the fun

01:32.759 --> 01:35.512
because I'll be working
the Community Policing Center

01:35.512 --> 01:36.888
with Smitty tomorrow.

01:36.888 --> 01:40.100
Ah. Only 10 more days
until no more T. O. s.

01:40.100 --> 01:42.561
[ Cellphone ringing ]
Mm.

01:42.561 --> 01:43.979
[ Cellphone beeps ]
Hey.

01:43.979 --> 01:46.523
I thought you were starting
college classes tonight.

01:46.523 --> 01:47.983
Nolan: I'm actually just about
to head into

01:47.983 --> 01:49.943
my Ethics and Criminal Law
class.

01:49.943 --> 01:51.737
But I'm having
second thoughts about

01:51.737 --> 01:53.989
identifying myself
as a police officer.

01:53.989 --> 01:55.324
<i>I mean, I should, right?</i>

01:55.324 --> 01:56.074
No.
No.
Yeah.

01:56.074 --> 01:57.826
That's...not helpful.

01:57.826 --> 01:58.952
<i>Why shouldn't you?</i>

01:58.952 --> 02:00.370
<i>Because it'll isolate him</i>
<i>right away.</i>

02:00.370 --> 02:02.956
You think I introduce myself
as homeless at school?

02:02.956 --> 02:05.500
Unless you want the class
to be about you,

02:05.500 --> 02:07.127
I'd keep your head down
and blend in.
[ Bell rings ]

02:07.127 --> 02:08.962
Good evening.
I'm Professor Ryan,

02:08.962 --> 02:11.548
and this is
Ethics and Criminal Justice.

02:11.548 --> 02:14.843
Now, tell me, what do
those words make you think?

02:14.843 --> 02:18.597
That...the two don't go
together.
Why?

02:18.597 --> 02:22.309
Because the criminal justice
system is inherently biased,

02:22.309 --> 02:24.895
designed to punish poor people
and people of color.

02:24.895 --> 02:26.480
Okay, so if that's a problem,
what is a solution?

02:26.480 --> 02:28.649
Defund the police,
for starters.

02:28.649 --> 02:30.359
Anyone disagree?

02:30.359 --> 02:32.527
Uh, well, I don't think
it's quite that simple ‐‐

02:32.527 --> 02:34.321
just defunding the police.

02:34.321 --> 02:36.698
Defunding doesn't mean
get rid of cops.

02:36.698 --> 02:38.158
It means
stop prioritizing them

02:38.158 --> 02:39.326
over people
they're supposed to serve.

02:39.326 --> 02:41.787
Yeah, no, I appreciate that,
and I agree.

02:41.787 --> 02:44.498
I think a lot more money needs
to be invested in communities,

02:44.498 --> 02:47.209
but it will take time
for those investments

02:47.209 --> 02:49.127
to effect any <i>real</i> change.

02:49.127 --> 02:51.755
If we drastically cut policing
before that happens,

02:51.755 --> 02:53.924
it would leave people
unprotected.

02:53.924 --> 02:55.801
It can't be worse
than it is now.

02:55.801 --> 02:57.678
Sure, it can.

02:57.678 --> 02:59.221
Don't you agree?

02:59.221 --> 03:01.807
Oh, I'm not here to agree
or to pick sides.

03:01.807 --> 03:03.558
Ethics are often at odds
with the law.

03:03.558 --> 03:05.185
What's right
and what is legal

03:05.185 --> 03:07.688
are very often
all too different.

03:07.688 --> 03:11.566
And that tension is what
we are here to explore.

03:11.566 --> 03:13.944
And it is going to get
uncomfortable,

03:13.944 --> 03:16.029
so y'all better strap in.

03:16.029 --> 03:19.533
♪ Whoa, oh, oh, oh, oh, oh,
whoa, oh, oh ♪

03:19.533 --> 03:21.868
♪ I'm gonna win for you ♪

03:21.868 --> 03:25.789
♪ Like I know
you want me to do ♪

03:25.789 --> 03:27.582
By then,
the class had ended,

03:27.582 --> 03:28.959
and I still hadn't
identified myself.

03:28.959 --> 03:30.544
Did I make a mistake?

03:30.544 --> 03:32.254
I can't answer that
for you.

03:32.254 --> 03:33.713
As a cop, you have to judge
social situations

03:33.713 --> 03:35.215
on a case‐by‐case basis.

03:35.215 --> 03:37.801
I just hate the feeling
like I'm hiding something.

03:37.801 --> 03:40.720
<i>All</i> of these people can't be
undercover cops, can they?

03:40.720 --> 03:42.097
Okay, so, think of
the undercover world

03:42.097 --> 03:43.473
like high school, right?

03:43.473 --> 03:44.808
So, first,
you have your UCs.

03:44.808 --> 03:46.518
They are like
the star quarterbacks.

03:46.518 --> 03:48.186
No undercover operation
can happen without them,

03:48.186 --> 03:49.020
and they know it.

03:49.020 --> 03:50.021
They take
the most risk,

03:50.021 --> 03:51.690
and they reap
the most reward.

03:51.690 --> 03:53.150
Meaning?
They get laid.

03:53.150 --> 03:54.192
A lot.
Oh.

03:54.192 --> 03:56.153
Then you have
your Case Officers.

03:56.153 --> 03:57.446
They're like
the debate team.

03:57.446 --> 03:58.905
They think they're smarter
than everyone else,

03:58.905 --> 04:01.074
and they see themselves
as puppet masters

04:01.074 --> 04:03.660
who use UCs as just a tool
in their kit.

04:03.660 --> 04:05.412
I'm guessing they don't get laid
near as much.

04:05.412 --> 04:07.789
Correct. Then you have
your Tech Squad.

04:07.789 --> 04:09.249
They're like the hackers.

04:09.249 --> 04:10.459
They basically <i>are</i> smarter
than everyone else,

04:10.459 --> 04:12.085
but they have
a real criminal streak.

04:12.085 --> 04:14.129
They commit legal burglaries
and break‐ins,

04:14.129 --> 04:15.464
planting
cameras and bugs.

04:15.464 --> 04:17.382
Finally,
you have your Freshmen.

04:17.382 --> 04:19.718
They're easily identifiable.
Just off patrol.

04:19.718 --> 04:21.303
Still at
that awkward stage

04:21.303 --> 04:22.763
of trying to let
their hair grow out,

04:22.763 --> 04:24.723
where they're
mullet‐adjacent.

04:24.723 --> 04:26.224
So <i>you</i> were
a star quarterback.

04:26.224 --> 04:29.936
Oh, baby,
I was the Heisman Trophy.

04:29.936 --> 04:32.314
Lucy: Alright, thanks.
You're good to go.

04:32.314 --> 04:34.149
Hey, do you work the convention
every year?

04:34.149 --> 04:36.318
No. L. A. hasn't hosted one
in a long time.

04:36.318 --> 04:37.486
But I did go
with Isabel once.

04:37.486 --> 04:38.695
What kind of classes
do they teach?

04:38.695 --> 04:40.155
No idea.

04:40.155 --> 04:42.574
Patrol isn't allowed to know
UC trade secrets.

04:42.574 --> 04:45.202
So I just ordered room service,
worked on my tan.

04:45.202 --> 04:46.912
[ Chuckles ]
<i>♪ Don't talk, just listen ♪</i>

04:46.912 --> 04:49.831
Bradford!
Mack!

04:49.831 --> 04:52.459
Ugh! You bastard!
You get prettier with age.

04:52.459 --> 04:54.294
Yeah, and you're still
the same part Neanderthal.

04:54.294 --> 04:55.962
[ Chuckles ]
Lucy Chen, Mack Daniels.

04:55.962 --> 04:57.297
Hey, how are you?

04:57.297 --> 04:58.799
Oh, hi.
Nice to meet you.

04:58.799 --> 05:00.050
Beth, how are the kids?

05:00.050 --> 05:02.177
Oh, uh, this is actually,
uh, my friend Candace.

05:02.177 --> 05:04.596
Candace: Hi. Mack's right.
You are pretty.

05:04.596 --> 05:06.306
[ Chuckles ]

05:06.306 --> 05:08.517
Uh, Chen, why don't you go
and get Candace's info?

05:08.517 --> 05:10.769
Yeah.
Mack, come on
over here, bud.

05:10.769 --> 05:13.230
Uh‐oh.
Am I in trouble?

05:15.106 --> 05:17.484
If you wanna run around on Beth,
that's your business.

05:17.484 --> 05:19.528
But did you really expect me
not to notice?

05:19.528 --> 05:21.279
Notice what?
Your pupils, man.

05:21.279 --> 05:22.572
They're pinpoints.

05:22.572 --> 05:24.074
You're looking 5‐50.
What are you on?

05:24.074 --> 05:26.243
It's just a little Oxy.
Okay?

05:26.243 --> 05:27.911
Relax,
I got a prescription.

05:27.911 --> 05:29.788
Jacked up my shoulder on the job
about a month back.

05:29.788 --> 05:31.665
Pain's a, uh, mother.

05:31.665 --> 05:35.502
Mack!
I got a spa appointment.

05:35.502 --> 05:36.461
I gotta go.

05:36.461 --> 05:37.587
Hey, it's good
seeing you, bro.

05:37.587 --> 05:39.464
Yeah. You, too.
[ Engine starts ]

05:39.464 --> 05:40.674
<i>♪ Shut up more</i>
<i>and then listen ♪</i>
[ Door closes ]

05:40.674 --> 05:42.425
<i>♪ Some of y'all need</i>
<i>to just muzzle up ♪</i>

05:42.425 --> 05:45.637
<i>♪ I got hits to throw,</i>
<i>you wanna muscle up ♪</i>

05:45.637 --> 05:47.764
He seems...nice.
[ Chuckles ]

05:47.764 --> 05:49.266
Yeah, believe it or not,
he used to be

05:49.266 --> 05:50.725
the most clean‐cut guy
I ever met.

05:53.270 --> 05:54.855
James, it's good to see you.

05:54.855 --> 05:56.314
Am I, uh, still on for

05:56.314 --> 05:57.816
Aaron and Michael tutoring
tomorrow night?

05:57.816 --> 06:00.193
Just Aaron.
Michael has drama club.

06:00.193 --> 06:02.404
That boy's such a ham.
I love him.

06:02.404 --> 06:03.905
Who's this?
This is Silas.

06:03.905 --> 06:05.323
Silas, good to meet you.

06:05.323 --> 06:07.409
I'm, uh, Jackson,
and this is Smitty.

06:07.409 --> 06:09.578
Jackson.
Last name West.

06:09.578 --> 06:10.829
Badge number, please?
For my records.

06:10.829 --> 06:13.874
3‐3‐3‐5‐6.

06:13.874 --> 06:15.917
Badge number?

06:15.917 --> 06:18.003
2‐8‐7‐1‐7.

06:18.003 --> 06:19.170
First name, please.

06:19.170 --> 06:20.297
Smitty's sufficient.

06:20.297 --> 06:22.757
Silas is the eyes and ears
of the neighborhood.

06:22.757 --> 06:24.759
He does a daily patrol,
gives me a heads‐up

06:24.759 --> 06:26.428
on problems
that need fixing.

06:26.428 --> 06:27.596
Anything we should
know about?

06:27.596 --> 06:29.222
Well, City Sanitation
neglected to empty

06:29.222 --> 06:30.849
the Dumpster
in front of Matteo's Deli.

06:30.849 --> 06:32.350
That will attract rodents.

06:32.350 --> 06:34.352
And a Cadet Blue
1978 Dodge Aspen

06:34.352 --> 06:35.896
is blocking
Sally Nelson's driveway,

06:35.896 --> 06:36.897
and she has work
at 10:00.

06:36.897 --> 06:38.523
Kid would make a good CI.

06:38.523 --> 06:39.941
Forget it.

06:39.941 --> 06:41.985
Silas is here because
he wants to help his neighbors,

06:41.985 --> 06:43.778
not make it easier
for you to hassle them.

06:43.778 --> 06:46.865
Of course. That's <i>not</i> what
we're looking for.

06:46.865 --> 06:49.326
Look, I can call the city
and have them tow away the Aspen

06:49.326 --> 06:50.702
so Sally can get to work.

06:50.702 --> 06:51.953
Is there anything else
we can help you with?

06:51.953 --> 06:54.539
Um, I've actually
made a list of potholes,

06:54.539 --> 06:56.708
and they can cause accidents,
car damage.

06:56.708 --> 06:58.376
But the Bureau
of Street Services

06:58.376 --> 06:59.502
doesn't return
my telephone calls.

06:59.502 --> 07:02.756
Smitty, doesn't your uncle
work for City Services?

07:02.756 --> 07:04.841
Ugh ‐‐ Artie. Yes.

07:04.841 --> 07:06.801
Guy is <i>such</i> a slacker.

07:06.801 --> 07:09.512
Can you call him
about the potholes?

07:09.512 --> 07:11.222
No.

07:11.222 --> 07:12.641
I owe him money.

07:12.641 --> 07:13.933
Okay, fine.

07:13.933 --> 07:15.226
Give me the number,
and I'll call.

07:15.226 --> 07:16.519
Do you really think
there could be trouble

07:16.519 --> 07:17.270
at this convention?

07:17.270 --> 07:18.480
Absolutely.

07:18.480 --> 07:20.690
Criminals would kill
to infiltrate this place.

07:20.690 --> 07:22.901
The damage that
undercover operations do

07:22.901 --> 07:24.569
to their business
is incredible.

07:24.569 --> 07:27.656
[ Cellphone ringing ]

07:27.656 --> 07:28.698
[ Cellphone clicks ]

07:28.698 --> 07:30.784
June!
Wh‐‐ Are you here?

07:30.784 --> 07:32.744
<i>Oh, good.</i>
<i>You're at the convention.</i>

07:32.744 --> 07:34.329
<i>I'm scheduled to teach</i>
<i>a seminar this morning,</i>

07:34.329 --> 07:35.205
<i>but I can't get there.</i>

07:35.205 --> 07:36.498
<i>Can you fill in for me?</i>

07:36.498 --> 07:37.749
<i>It's the same class</i>
<i>you used to teach.</i>

07:37.749 --> 07:38.667
<i>You could do it</i>
<i>in your sleep.</i>

07:38.667 --> 07:40.752
I can't.
I'm working security.

07:40.752 --> 07:43.546
<i>Please. You still owe me</i>
<i>from that op in Bakersfield,</i>

07:43.546 --> 07:45.715
<i>and you know I wouldn't ask</i>
<i>if I didn't have to.</i>

07:45.715 --> 07:47.092
Go ahead.
I got this covered.

07:47.092 --> 07:48.635
Go ahead.

07:48.635 --> 07:50.428
Okay.
Uh, sure.

07:50.428 --> 07:51.971
<i>Thanks.</i>
<i>I'll text you the details.</i>

07:51.971 --> 07:53.139
<i>You are the best.</i>

07:53.139 --> 07:53.932
[ Chuckles ]
[ Cellphone clicks ]

07:53.932 --> 07:55.558
What's the seminar on?

07:55.558 --> 07:59.354
Women make up just 12%
of law enforcement.

07:59.354 --> 08:03.316
But they're attacked almost
twice as often as male officers.

08:03.316 --> 08:06.194
And yet, male officers are

08:06.194 --> 08:08.738
three times more likely
to fire their weapon,

08:08.738 --> 08:12.283
they are three times more likely
to get injured while on duty,

08:12.283 --> 08:16.371
and they make up 95%
of citizen complaints.

08:16.371 --> 08:19.207
Which begs the question,
are women just better cops?

08:19.207 --> 08:20.875
Oh, you better believe it.

08:20.875 --> 08:23.753
[ Cheers and applause ]

08:23.753 --> 08:25.130
[ Harper speaking indistinctly ]

08:25.130 --> 08:26.506
You're not supposed to be
listening.

08:26.506 --> 08:28.133
Why? 'Cause they don't
trust patrol

08:28.133 --> 08:29.592
with all their
Secret Squirrel stuff?

08:29.592 --> 08:31.594
It doesn't matter why.
Rules are rules.

08:31.594 --> 08:33.763
And I'm already on thin ice,
so I'm outta here.

08:33.763 --> 08:36.683
This seminar today is about
being a female undercover cop

08:36.683 --> 08:38.768
and the unique risks
that that poses.

08:38.768 --> 08:42.564
Now, I will warn you, this is
not gonna be an easy ride.

08:42.564 --> 08:46.192
Some of what you're about to see
is hard to watch.

08:46.192 --> 08:49.654
But if we can learn from the UCs
who died in these videos,

08:49.654 --> 08:52.657
then maybe
we can save some lives.

08:52.657 --> 08:54.284
Are you with me?

08:54.284 --> 08:57.245
[ Cheers and applause ]

08:57.245 --> 08:59.247
♪♪

08:59.247 --> 09:00.707
Chen.
Yes?

09:00.707 --> 09:02.417
Thought you were running
to the bathroom.

09:02.417 --> 09:04.544
I was. I am.

09:04.544 --> 09:05.253
Sorry.

09:11.384 --> 09:12.761
Jackson: Next time he calls
about potholes,

09:12.761 --> 09:13.970
take it seriously, okay?

09:13.970 --> 09:17.057
Yes, I work with Smitty.

09:17.057 --> 09:20.643
Yeah. No.
No, I‐I <i>won't</i> tell him that.

09:20.643 --> 09:22.228
Because it's disgusting.

09:22.228 --> 09:24.355
[ Screaming ]
No! No! No! No!

09:24.355 --> 09:26.357
No! No!

09:26.357 --> 09:28.026
[ Tires screech ]

09:28.026 --> 09:29.319
My baby's in the back!

09:29.319 --> 09:30.695
7‐Adam‐07, carjacking,

09:30.695 --> 09:33.031
suspect headed westbound
on Fourth near Waverly.

09:33.031 --> 09:34.866
I'm on foot.
I need any unit in the area.

09:34.866 --> 09:36.659
[ Woman screaming indistinctly ]

09:36.659 --> 09:42.290
♪♪

09:42.290 --> 09:47.796
♪♪

09:47.796 --> 09:49.464
♪ Whacha got, whatcha got? ♪

09:49.464 --> 09:52.092
[ Horse neighs ]
♪ Into the wild
and when you get up? ♪

09:52.092 --> 09:53.384
♪ And in the morning ♪

09:53.384 --> 09:54.719
I guess you didn't need
that assist after all.

09:54.719 --> 09:56.179
You're...?

09:56.179 --> 09:58.848
A cop on a horse?
Yep.

09:58.848 --> 09:59.974
Any other suspects?

09:59.974 --> 10:02.769
No.
Can you watch him?

10:02.769 --> 10:04.104
Victim said her baby
was in the car.

10:04.104 --> 10:07.148
♪ Like an A‐list star
in a movie ♪

10:07.148 --> 10:08.900
[ Gasps ] Oh!

10:08.900 --> 10:11.194
Ma'am, <i>that's</i> your baby?

10:11.194 --> 10:12.195
Yeah.

10:12.195 --> 10:14.697
Oh!
[ Dog whimpering ]

10:14.697 --> 10:15.740
Oh, I'm sorry.

10:15.740 --> 10:17.492
[ Horse neighs ]

10:17.492 --> 10:18.493
So you were spying
on one of the seminars?

10:18.493 --> 10:20.745
No.

10:20.745 --> 10:23.039
Maybe a little bit.

10:23.039 --> 10:25.041
I mean, what's the big deal?
I'm a cop, too.

10:25.041 --> 10:26.709
The likelihood
of patrol officers

10:26.709 --> 10:27.919
getting fired
or flaming out

10:27.919 --> 10:29.295
are much higher
than ranked officers.

10:29.295 --> 10:31.965
The information and tactics
the CCOA present

10:31.965 --> 10:34.300
are so unique
and so sensitive,

10:34.300 --> 10:36.136
they're literally
on a need‐to‐know basis.

10:36.136 --> 10:38.138
Got it?

10:38.138 --> 10:39.722
Yeah.

10:40.974 --> 10:42.934
Tim?
Beth.

10:42.934 --> 10:44.477
I'm here to surprise Mack.

10:44.477 --> 10:46.187
He's barely been home
the last three months.

10:46.187 --> 10:48.815
I bet. Yeah, undercover work's
a full‐time gig.

10:48.815 --> 10:50.024
Is he here yet?

10:51.401 --> 10:53.903
Yeah. He rolled through
a few hours ago.

10:53.903 --> 10:54.863
It's great seeing you.

10:54.863 --> 10:56.114
You, too.

10:57.615 --> 10:59.325
Seriously?

10:59.325 --> 11:00.577
You're not gonna give her
a heads‐up?

11:00.577 --> 11:03.580
No way I'm getting
in the middle of that.

11:03.580 --> 11:05.540
Tim.
Check this out.

11:05.540 --> 11:07.959
[ Camera shutter clicks ]
Those cars belong to
the undercover cops.

11:07.959 --> 11:09.169
Well, they'll have
switched‐out license plates

11:09.169 --> 11:10.211
so criminals
can't ID them.

11:10.211 --> 11:13.047
But they can't cover
the VIN numbers.

11:13.047 --> 11:15.133
If he gets those numbers,
he'll be able to identify them.

11:15.133 --> 11:16.968
Gun.
Back pocket.

11:16.968 --> 11:18.845
Hey! Police!
Hold up!

11:18.845 --> 11:24.642
♪♪

11:24.642 --> 11:30.440
♪♪

11:30.440 --> 11:31.941
All units, be advised,
we have a perimeter breach.

11:31.941 --> 11:34.110
White male, blue ballcap,
gray jacket, blue jeans.

11:34.110 --> 11:35.612
Made it in through
the south rear door.

11:35.612 --> 11:37.071
Armed with a handgun,
and may be targeting police.

11:40.325 --> 11:42.327
He won't get far.
Hotel's on lockdown,

11:42.327 --> 11:43.369
and his description
just went out

11:43.369 --> 11:45.205
to 200
armed police officers.

11:45.205 --> 11:47.207
Really, he's trapped
in here with us.

11:47.207 --> 11:48.124
[ Flashlight clicks ]

11:48.124 --> 11:50.001
Yeah, that description's
useless now.

11:50.001 --> 11:51.336
[ Radio beeps ]

11:51.336 --> 11:53.129
Be advised, our suspect
no longer has on

11:53.129 --> 11:55.215
a ballcap or jacket.

11:55.215 --> 11:59.135
Which means we are searching for
a white guy in blue jeans.

11:59.135 --> 12:00.845
[ Indistinct conversations ]

12:03.473 --> 12:04.849
Do you see that?

12:04.849 --> 12:07.018
Yeah, that could be our guy.
Could just be a twitchy UC.

12:07.018 --> 12:09.395
They're hardwired to avoid
uniformed cops.

12:09.395 --> 12:11.856
You think you can tell if he's
a cop just by talking to him?

12:11.856 --> 12:13.191
Is that a challenge?
Yep.

12:15.693 --> 12:16.653
How's it going?

12:16.653 --> 12:17.987
Ah.

12:19.155 --> 12:21.574
Here for the convention?

12:21.574 --> 12:23.201
I'm not really
supposed to say.

12:23.201 --> 12:24.869
That's a yes.
I'd kill to work undercover.

12:24.869 --> 12:26.037
God, me, too.

12:26.037 --> 12:26.871
You must have
the best stories.

12:26.871 --> 12:28.581
[ Scoffs ] Nah.

12:28.581 --> 12:30.333
Oh, come on.
Give us one.

12:30.333 --> 12:31.125
I've only been
a year on the job.

12:31.125 --> 12:32.835
I've never seen
any real action.

12:32.835 --> 12:36.214
Alright, well, this one time,
a couple years back,

12:36.214 --> 12:37.924
I get in with
this biker gang,

12:37.924 --> 12:40.260
and we're movin'
a hell‐ton'a smack.

12:40.260 --> 12:42.178
Now, the buyer,
he smells a rat,

12:42.178 --> 12:44.222
and suddenly, I've got
six sawed‐off shotties

12:44.222 --> 12:45.807
right to my grill.
Mm.

12:45.807 --> 12:47.600
They wanted me to try the batch,
make sure it wasn't bunk.

12:47.600 --> 12:48.893
What'd you do?

12:48.893 --> 12:50.061
Man, I got high
as the Hindenburg

12:50.061 --> 12:51.354
and came down
just as messy.

12:51.354 --> 12:52.855
[ Mimics buzzer ]
Sorry. Wrong answer.

12:52.855 --> 12:55.608
[ Tasers clicking ]

12:55.608 --> 12:57.610
[ Grunts ] Ah.

12:57.610 --> 12:58.903
Real undercover cops
don't behave

12:58.903 --> 13:00.697
like characters in movies.
[ Grunts ]

13:00.697 --> 13:02.532
Taste the drugs,

13:02.532 --> 13:05.576
your case,
your career are shot.
[ Handcuffs click ]

13:05.576 --> 13:07.745
[ Radio beeps ]
Suspect in custody.

13:07.745 --> 13:10.456
Thanks for the assist.
Ah, no problem.

13:10.456 --> 13:11.958
I was giving a talk at
the local elementary school.

13:11.958 --> 13:13.626
Yeah, I gotta admit,

13:13.626 --> 13:16.170
I've actually never seen
a cop on a horse before.

13:16.170 --> 13:17.964
Well, not out on the street,
anyway.

13:17.964 --> 13:19.924
It's...weird.
[ Chuckles ]

13:19.924 --> 13:21.634
You must have been looking
in the wrong direction.

13:21.634 --> 13:24.012
Yeah, well, I am not now.

13:24.012 --> 13:25.471
[ Horse snorts ]

13:25.471 --> 13:28.850
Officer Jackson West,
badge number 3‐3‐3‐5‐6.

13:28.850 --> 13:30.727
What's up, Silas?
I don't know him.

13:30.727 --> 13:32.270
Uh, this is Officer Young.

13:32.270 --> 13:35.398
Isaac.
Badge number 2‐9‐1‐9‐6.

13:35.398 --> 13:37.275
And this here's Ruby,
official police horse

13:37.275 --> 13:38.860
of the West Adams
Mounted Patrol.

13:38.860 --> 13:39.986
Does she have
a badge number?

13:39.986 --> 13:41.779
No, but she lives in
stall number 11.

13:41.779 --> 13:43.197
Uh, how's patrol?

13:43.197 --> 13:44.157
Is there anything else
we can do?

13:44.157 --> 13:47.201
Actually...

13:47.201 --> 13:49.579
a sprinkler head
at Edgewood Park broke off

13:49.579 --> 13:50.997
and is spraying the swings.

13:50.997 --> 13:52.290
Okay.
Well, I am on it.

13:52.290 --> 13:53.833
It's, uh ‐‐
it's nice to meet you.

13:53.833 --> 13:54.792
Yeah, you, too.

13:58.087 --> 13:59.630
You two are looking
at each other funny.

13:59.630 --> 14:01.299
[ Laughs ]

14:01.299 --> 14:03.301
I am his wife!
Open the damn door!

14:03.301 --> 14:04.927
He doesn't want
to see you!

14:04.927 --> 14:06.763
Mack, I'm done.
Can you hear me?

14:06.763 --> 14:08.848
You're never gonna see
your sons again!

14:08.848 --> 14:10.058
What's going on?
Are you okay?

14:10.058 --> 14:11.559
Mack's in there
with some stripper whore.

14:11.559 --> 14:13.770
[ Crying ] He's wasted
out of his mind.

14:13.770 --> 14:15.063
♪♪

14:15.063 --> 14:16.064
What's going on?
Nothing.

14:16.064 --> 14:17.231
We're just hanging out.

14:17.231 --> 14:18.107
Get Mack.
I need to see him.

14:18.107 --> 14:19.400
No, he's sleeping ‐‐
I think.

14:19.400 --> 14:20.818
I don't know!
He won't talk to me.

14:20.818 --> 14:22.111
Open the door.

14:22.111 --> 14:23.613
No, I can't.
Open ‐‐

14:23.613 --> 14:24.822
Back up!

14:25.698 --> 14:27.492
♪ Still ain't the crew ♪
Mack.

14:27.492 --> 14:29.952
♪ Buy the same fits,
but you still ain't the crew ♪

14:29.952 --> 14:31.079
He's not breathing.

14:31.079 --> 14:32.538
What did you do?!
Nothing.

14:32.538 --> 14:33.539
We were just partying.

14:33.539 --> 14:34.540
Control, 7‐Adam‐19,

14:34.540 --> 14:36.209
send an RA
to the Augustin Hotel,

14:36.209 --> 14:38.586
9212 West 6th Street,
Room 623.

14:38.586 --> 14:40.922
Adult male,
possible OD.
[ Radio beeps ]

14:40.922 --> 14:42.090
♪ That ain't you,
that ain't you ♪

14:42.090 --> 14:43.800
♪ That ain't you,
that ain't you ♪

14:43.800 --> 14:44.967
Come on, Mack.

14:44.967 --> 14:46.469
♪ Guns out ♪

14:46.469 --> 14:47.887
Come on.
Wake up, Mack!

14:47.887 --> 14:49.222
Come on.
Tim. Narcan.

14:49.222 --> 14:51.599
♪♪

14:51.599 --> 14:53.101
[ Spray hisses ]

14:53.101 --> 14:56.896
♪♪

14:56.896 --> 14:59.065
♪ Got a team of boys, yeah ♪

14:59.065 --> 15:01.275
[ Gasps, coughs ]

15:01.275 --> 15:02.401
You're all right, man.
You're all right.

15:02.401 --> 15:03.986
I'm here, okay?
Beth's here.

15:03.986 --> 15:05.404
[ Gasps ]
You're okay, bud.

15:05.404 --> 15:08.616
Try and sit up.
Beth...baby...

15:08.616 --> 15:09.909
I can't do this anymore.

15:09.909 --> 15:11.744
Wait, wait, wait.

15:11.744 --> 15:13.037
Come back.
I love you.

15:13.037 --> 15:14.747
You said <i>I</i> was the one
you loved.

15:14.747 --> 15:16.415
♪ In a Lamborghini ♪

15:16.415 --> 15:18.876
♪ You could like the same,
but you still ain't the crew ♪

15:18.876 --> 15:21.546
Okay,
tell me the truth.

15:21.546 --> 15:23.214
Did working the convention
as a patrol officer

15:23.214 --> 15:24.799
feel like a demotion?

15:24.799 --> 15:26.092
At first, yes.

15:26.092 --> 15:30.054
But then, I don't know.
I got a contact anxiety high.

15:30.054 --> 15:32.807
I do not miss the constant fear
and the lying so much

15:32.807 --> 15:34.183
you don't know
what the truth is.

15:34.183 --> 15:35.268
Hey!

15:35.268 --> 15:36.060
I know you.

15:40.606 --> 15:42.066
Victor, right?

15:42.066 --> 15:43.484
Hey.
How you doing?

15:43.484 --> 15:44.986
Victor's
in my Ethics class.

15:44.986 --> 15:46.404
You're a cop.

15:46.404 --> 15:47.572
I can see why
you might think that.

15:47.572 --> 15:49.824
Um, but to be fair,
this uniform could also mean

15:49.824 --> 15:51.075
I'm a male stripper.
[ Cellphone camera shutter
clicks ]

15:51.075 --> 15:52.326
Whoa.
What's all that for?

15:52.326 --> 15:54.704
To show everyone in class
we got a narc inside.

15:54.704 --> 15:56.330
Victor. Hey.

15:56.330 --> 15:58.624
It's a little harsh.
Victor.

16:00.334 --> 16:03.087
Well...can't wait to hear
how class goes.

16:07.091 --> 16:08.384
[ Exhales sharply ]

16:08.384 --> 16:10.803
Hey.

16:10.803 --> 16:12.263
Were you trying to
kill yourself?

16:12.263 --> 16:14.307
[ Scoffs ]
God, Bradford, no.

16:14.307 --> 16:15.850
Okay, then what the hell
were you thinking?

16:15.850 --> 16:18.060
You told me you were taking Oxy
because you were injured.

16:18.060 --> 16:19.729
I was. Alright?

16:19.729 --> 16:21.647
I am.

16:21.647 --> 16:22.732
It was a mistake.

16:22.732 --> 16:23.900
A mistake?
Yeah.

16:23.900 --> 16:26.194
You downed opioids
with whiskey.

16:26.194 --> 16:27.486
Alright, that's not
pain management.

16:27.486 --> 16:30.156
That is a problem.
I know.

16:30.156 --> 16:32.033
I screwed up, okay?
Yeah.

16:32.033 --> 16:33.284
I was just trying
to push through the pain

16:33.284 --> 16:35.328
a‐a‐and keep working.

16:35.328 --> 16:37.163
It got away from me.
Y‐You know how it is.

16:37.163 --> 16:39.248
I do.

16:39.248 --> 16:40.666
And I know addicts
lie so much

16:40.666 --> 16:41.834
they don't know
what's true anymore.

16:41.834 --> 16:43.836
Hey, I am not your ex‐wife.
Really?

16:43.836 --> 16:46.631
'Cause from where I'm standing,
you look exactly like Isabel.

16:46.631 --> 16:48.466
Look, I'm not gonna make
the same mistake I did with her.

16:48.466 --> 16:50.551
You are going
into a program.

16:50.551 --> 16:52.845
Tomorrow.

16:52.845 --> 16:55.806
You can't keep doing this
to your family, Mack.

16:55.806 --> 16:57.892
I know.
I know.

16:57.892 --> 16:59.435
I will.

16:59.435 --> 17:01.437
I promise.

17:01.437 --> 17:07.610
♪♪

17:07.610 --> 17:09.153
[ Chuckles ]

17:10.613 --> 17:11.364
Hello.

17:11.364 --> 17:13.199
Hi.
Mm‐hmm.

17:13.199 --> 17:15.534
So, you know we're gonna have
to talk about it, right?

17:15.534 --> 17:19.580
Look, it was a momentary
lapse in judgement,

17:19.580 --> 17:21.582
and Tim has already scolded me
for listening in,

17:21.582 --> 17:23.251
but I gotta say, um,

17:23.251 --> 17:27.296
what I heard at your seminar
was amazing.

17:27.296 --> 17:29.840
I was a little rusty,
but thank you.

17:29.840 --> 17:31.217
Listen, I've been
thinking a lot

17:31.217 --> 17:33.052
about what I want to do

17:33.052 --> 17:35.429
once I'm eligible to test,
and...

17:35.429 --> 17:38.432
I think I could be really good
at undercover work.

17:38.432 --> 17:40.142
I would love to
pick your brain sometime ‐‐

17:40.142 --> 17:42.770
not about tactics,
just...

17:42.770 --> 17:45.731
what I should focus on
to prepare for the job.

17:45.731 --> 17:48.109
I actually ‐‐
I...have time

17:48.109 --> 17:49.944
for drinks right now,
if you want.

17:49.944 --> 17:51.862
Yeah. Great.

17:51.862 --> 17:53.072
Alright.
Uh...no.

17:53.072 --> 17:55.866
I have a homework thing
with Tamara.

17:55.866 --> 17:58.244
She won't mind if we do it
a little bit later.

17:58.244 --> 17:59.120
Let me just
give her a call.

17:59.120 --> 18:00.288
[ Cellphone beeping ]

18:00.288 --> 18:01.706
[ <i>Line ringing</i> ]

18:01.706 --> 18:03.332
Hey, it's me.

18:03.332 --> 18:05.751
Are we cool
if we do the interview

18:05.751 --> 18:06.961
a little bit later
tonight?

18:06.961 --> 18:08.212
Is 9:00
too late for you?

18:08.212 --> 18:09.880
Okay. Great.
I will see you then.

18:11.048 --> 18:12.425
[ Cellphone clicks ]
I am all yours.

18:12.425 --> 18:13.968
[ Cellphone ringing, beeps ]

18:13.968 --> 18:16.804
Hey. You know you owe me
big time, right?

18:16.804 --> 18:18.347
<i>Yeah, but can we keep</i>
<i>my tab open?</i>

18:18.347 --> 18:19.599
<i>I could use another assist.</i>

18:19.599 --> 18:21.767
Uh, I was about
to go out for drinks

18:21.767 --> 18:23.352
with a colleague of mine,
Lucy Chen.

18:23.352 --> 18:24.562
Hey.

18:24.562 --> 18:25.479
<i>I'm in a bind.</i>

18:25.479 --> 18:26.689
<i>Look, the real reason</i>

18:26.689 --> 18:27.940
<i>I couldn't make</i>
<i>the convention today</i>

18:27.940 --> 18:29.108
<i>is because</i>
<i>I spotted a tail</i>

18:29.108 --> 18:30.151
<i>on my way down</i>
<i>from Sacramento.</i>

18:30.151 --> 18:32.111
Who?
<i>I think it's the buyer</i>

18:32.111 --> 18:33.446
<i>in this op</i>
<i>I've been running.</i>

18:33.446 --> 18:34.322
<i>They're sniffing around</i>
<i>a big batch</i>

18:34.322 --> 18:35.865
<i>of liquid Fentanyl</i>
<i>I'm selling.</i>

18:35.865 --> 18:37.074
And you think
they're onto you?

18:37.074 --> 18:39.243
<i>I think there's</i>
<i>a lot of money in play</i>

18:39.243 --> 18:40.328
<i>and they're paranoid as hell.</i>

18:40.328 --> 18:42.121
Are they still
surveilling you?

18:42.121 --> 18:43.456
<i>Yeah,</i>
<i>I couldn't lose them.</i>

18:43.456 --> 18:45.916
<i>I think they put a tracker</i>
<i>on my car.</i>

18:45.916 --> 18:47.460
<i>Look, I'm at The Smoke House</i>
<i>in Burbank,</i>

18:47.460 --> 18:48.753
<i>but my whole team's</i>
<i>up in San Jose.</i>

18:48.753 --> 18:50.463
What are you driving?

18:50.463 --> 18:52.923
<i>Black Mustang GT.</i>
<i>They know me as Coco.</i>

18:52.923 --> 18:54.050
Alright,
I'm on my way.

18:54.050 --> 18:55.301
[ Cellphone beeps ]
Sorry.

18:55.301 --> 18:56.510
I'm gonna have
to call Grey now,

18:56.510 --> 18:57.845
and we're gonna have
to take a rain check

18:57.845 --> 18:59.305
on our drinks, but ‐‐
Totally.

19:01.015 --> 19:02.058
Unless you wanna
come with?

19:02.058 --> 19:05.061
♪♪

19:05.061 --> 19:07.396
[ Woman clears throat ]

19:07.396 --> 19:08.439
Narc.

19:08.439 --> 19:10.274
Hey.
There's no call for that.

19:10.274 --> 19:11.817
At least
let me explain first?

19:11.817 --> 19:13.402
Explain what?
That he's a cop.

19:13.402 --> 19:14.153
Yeah, I know.

19:14.153 --> 19:15.279
What do you mean,
you know?

19:15.279 --> 19:17.907
Well, I saw it
on his application

19:17.907 --> 19:19.283
when he signed up
for my class.

19:19.283 --> 19:20.618
And you didn't tell us?

19:20.618 --> 19:22.828
Oh, it wasn't
my decision to make.

19:22.828 --> 19:24.163
How can you say that?

19:24.163 --> 19:25.414
Cops have been spying
on people like us

19:25.414 --> 19:26.791
for 200 years.

19:26.791 --> 19:29.126
He could be taking this class
to get close to us,

19:29.126 --> 19:30.878
to get into LULAC
or Black Lives Matter.

19:30.878 --> 19:32.380
Oh, I'm not undercover.

19:32.380 --> 19:33.631
I'm ‐‐ I'm actually
just a rookie.

19:33.631 --> 19:34.799
Dude, stop lying.

19:34.799 --> 19:37.802
I'm not.
Um...

19:37.802 --> 19:40.846
Two years ago, I was working
construction back east.

19:40.846 --> 19:42.765
I moved out here
to join the police

19:42.765 --> 19:44.100
and make a difference.

19:44.100 --> 19:47.186
I'm actually taking this class
to finally get my degree.

19:47.186 --> 19:50.606
It's true.
I read his transcript.

19:50.606 --> 19:52.733
Plus, do you really think
the LAPD's gonna send

19:52.733 --> 19:55.319
a 40‐something‐year‐old
white guy to infiltrate BLM?

19:55.319 --> 19:57.113
Come on, now.
Probably not.

19:57.113 --> 19:58.989
He still should have
told us he's a cop.

19:58.989 --> 20:00.574
Hmm.

20:00.574 --> 20:03.119
Who here thinks that John
is ethically obligated

20:03.119 --> 20:05.037
to identify himself?

20:05.037 --> 20:06.288
I do.

20:06.288 --> 20:07.915
Why?

20:07.915 --> 20:10.167
This is supposed to be
a safe space.

20:10.167 --> 20:11.335
What if one of us
admitted to a crime

20:11.335 --> 20:12.837
in the middle of
a discussion?

20:12.837 --> 20:14.505
Well, then,
you'd be stupid.

20:14.505 --> 20:16.424
There are no
truly safe spaces ‐‐

20:16.424 --> 20:18.592
I mean, certainly not
in a college classroom.

20:18.592 --> 20:19.677
But believe it or not,

20:19.677 --> 20:22.054
I, uh,
was wrestling with

20:22.054 --> 20:24.682
whether or not to tell you
last night, and...

20:24.682 --> 20:27.351
honestly, I still don't know
what the right decision is.

20:27.351 --> 20:30.146
Okay, well,
let's explore that further.

20:30.146 --> 20:33.441
I want everyone in here
to write a five‐page essay.

20:33.441 --> 20:35.860
Tell me why or why not
you think that John had

20:35.860 --> 20:37.653
an ethical obligation
to tell us he's a cop.

20:37.653 --> 20:39.029
[ Students groaning ]

20:42.074 --> 20:44.869
[ Crickets chirping,
dog barking in distance ]

20:46.495 --> 20:47.329
[ Car door closes ]

20:47.329 --> 20:48.748
There's June's car.

21:06.348 --> 21:07.183
Tracker.

21:07.183 --> 21:08.768
What's the plan?

21:08.768 --> 21:10.811
[ Sighs ]
You go in, find June.

21:10.811 --> 21:12.730
Remember, her undercover name
is Coco.

21:12.730 --> 21:14.356
She's a friend in town.

21:14.356 --> 21:16.108
Buy her a drink,
chat her up.

21:16.108 --> 21:18.611
I will hang back and try
and spot who her tails are.

21:18.611 --> 21:21.155
Okay.
You up for this?

21:21.155 --> 21:22.948
Hell yeah.

21:22.948 --> 21:24.700
[ Pool balls clack ]

21:24.700 --> 21:26.452
Coco?

21:26.452 --> 21:30.122
Hey.
Hey.

21:30.122 --> 21:32.333
Harper found a tracker outside.
We think they're here.

21:32.333 --> 21:33.626
Yeah, I know.
One's at your 4:00.

21:33.626 --> 21:35.294
Haven't spotted
his backup yet.

21:35.294 --> 21:36.045
[ Clears throat ]

21:36.045 --> 21:39.298
♪♪

21:39.298 --> 21:40.966
Hey, honey.
Can I get you something?

21:40.966 --> 21:43.177
Yeah, sure. Uh, I will have
what she's having.

21:43.177 --> 21:44.762
Do you want another one?
Sure.

21:44.762 --> 21:48.349
Make it three.

21:48.349 --> 21:49.892
Coco.

21:49.892 --> 21:52.520
Hey, what a coincidence, seeing
you all the way down here.

21:52.520 --> 21:54.647
Like hell.
You followed me.

21:54.647 --> 21:56.482
We got a lot of money
on the line with this deal,

21:56.482 --> 21:59.360
so we need to be
very careful.

21:59.360 --> 22:02.196
A lot of people in
this business, you know...

22:02.196 --> 22:04.031
they don't
have integrity.

22:04.031 --> 22:05.741
Yeah, 'cause you're
just filled with integrity,

22:05.741 --> 22:08.369
aren't you, Sato?

22:08.369 --> 22:11.872
Oh, you say my name in front of
someone that <i>I</i> don't know?

22:11.872 --> 22:13.374
What is wrong with you?

22:13.374 --> 22:14.959
No, what's wrong
with <i>you?</i>

22:14.959 --> 22:16.669
No one asked you to sit.

22:18.712 --> 22:20.172
Who is this bitch?

22:22.132 --> 22:23.843
Oh, you just
killed yourself.

22:23.843 --> 22:27.680
I'm looking at an empty chair
right there.

22:27.680 --> 22:30.724
Then who's gonna conduct
the hydrogenation process?

22:30.724 --> 22:32.351
Who's gonna perform
the molecular synthesis

22:32.351 --> 22:33.686
to get the acid tables
balanced?

22:33.686 --> 22:34.895
You get that wrong,
you're gonna have

22:34.895 --> 22:35.771
buyers with brain bleed.

22:35.771 --> 22:38.148
You're the chemist.

22:38.148 --> 22:40.150
She's the chemist.

22:40.150 --> 22:41.360
Yeah, she is.

22:41.360 --> 22:43.320
Now back off.

22:43.320 --> 22:45.406
And tell your boss
the price just went up 5%

22:45.406 --> 22:46.448
for the lack of trust.

22:46.448 --> 22:48.701
Oh, I don't think so.

22:48.701 --> 22:50.494
Let's take a walk,

22:50.494 --> 22:53.038
talk about this somewhere
a little more private.

22:53.038 --> 22:54.081
♪♪

22:54.081 --> 22:55.082
Hmm?

22:59.086 --> 23:01.839
We're gonna go
for a little ride.

23:01.839 --> 23:03.632
Think about why, uh, I got
such a bad feeling about you.

23:03.632 --> 23:05.467
[ Grunts ]

23:05.467 --> 23:07.094
Harper:
These guys are cops.

23:07.094 --> 23:08.679
They put a tracker
on your car.

23:08.679 --> 23:10.723
Got a bad feeling
about <i>me,</i> huh?

23:10.723 --> 23:12.808
Hey, we're not cops.

23:12.808 --> 23:14.894
You want me to do 'em here
or take 'em to the farm?

23:14.894 --> 23:16.854
Hey, you gotta
believe me.

23:16.854 --> 23:18.731
Coco, you know me.

23:18.731 --> 23:19.690
Then what's with
the tracker?

23:19.690 --> 23:22.026
Salonga wanted you
surveilled,

23:22.026 --> 23:23.485
in case you guys tried
to rip us off.

23:23.485 --> 23:25.154
I swear.

23:25.154 --> 23:27.907
Look, we want this deal
to happen.

23:27.907 --> 23:29.325
We <i>need</i> this deal
to happen, okay?

23:29.325 --> 23:30.868
We just wanted to
make sure.

23:30.868 --> 23:32.202
Well, now you are.

23:32.202 --> 23:34.622
But the price
just went up 10%.

23:34.622 --> 23:36.790
Consider it a tax
for pissing me off.

23:36.790 --> 23:38.125
Salonga ain't gonna go
for that.

23:38.125 --> 23:39.919
Hmm, then this is goodbye.
I got plenty of other buyers.

23:39.919 --> 23:40.794
Yeah, okay, okay!

23:43.714 --> 23:45.215
I'll make it happen.

23:45.215 --> 23:46.800
But she comes, too.

23:46.800 --> 23:48.552
At that price, I want her
to test the product

23:48.552 --> 23:51.221
in front of us to make sure
that it's pure.

23:51.221 --> 23:53.057
Forget it. No.
She doesn't go out on buys.

23:53.057 --> 23:55.392
What? N‐No.
I'll go.

23:55.392 --> 23:58.020
I've already spent my share
of the money in my head.

23:58.020 --> 24:00.564
I'll call you on this phone
with the new location.

24:00.564 --> 24:02.441
And you better pick up
on the first ring.

24:02.441 --> 24:03.317
Now piss off.

24:05.152 --> 24:07.237
Come on.

24:07.237 --> 24:12.034
♪♪

24:12.034 --> 24:16.121
[ Engine starts, tires screech ]

24:16.121 --> 24:18.374
I can't believe
we just did that.

24:18.374 --> 24:19.959
"You want me to do them here
or take 'em to the farm?"

24:19.959 --> 24:22.044
You are <i>so</i> badass!

24:22.044 --> 24:24.254
Wait, how much do you know
about opioid chemistry?

24:24.254 --> 24:25.965
I mean, just what they
taught me at the Academy.

24:25.965 --> 24:28.425
But I got straight A's
in high school chemistry, so...

24:28.425 --> 24:30.678
Then you're gonna have
some homework to do.

24:33.305 --> 24:34.431
What time is it?

24:36.684 --> 24:40.145
Hey.
Look, I am <i>so</i> sorry.

24:40.145 --> 24:42.564
It's cool.
No, it's not.

24:42.564 --> 24:44.650
Drinks turned into
this undercover thing,

24:44.650 --> 24:48.195
which was super cool ‐‐
but not the point.

24:48.195 --> 24:51.824
Look, there's no excuse
for me leaving you hanging.

24:51.824 --> 24:53.742
Can you do the interview now?
Or tonight?

24:53.742 --> 24:54.576
When is your paper due?

24:54.576 --> 24:55.703
It's fine.

24:55.703 --> 24:57.037
The drunk lady
across the hall

24:57.037 --> 24:59.289
used to be
a luchadora.

24:59.289 --> 25:00.165
I'll just ask her.

25:00.165 --> 25:01.250
What?

25:01.250 --> 25:03.043
Mexican wrestler.
No. No.

25:03.043 --> 25:05.629
Look, give me
another chance.

25:05.629 --> 25:06.922
Okay? Tonight.

25:06.922 --> 25:08.757
I promise
I'll be there.

25:08.757 --> 25:11.176
Okay. Sure.

25:11.176 --> 25:12.511
Now I gotta
get to school.

25:12.511 --> 25:13.762
Okay.

25:13.762 --> 25:16.181
♪♪

25:16.181 --> 25:18.183
[ Knock on door ]

25:18.183 --> 25:19.727
You get my report
on Mack Daniels?

25:19.727 --> 25:23.564
Yeah, I did.

25:23.564 --> 25:26.275
Are you sure this is the way
you want things to go?

25:26.275 --> 25:28.235
He'll get fired,
might do jail time.

25:28.235 --> 25:29.903
Mack didn't get hurt
a month ago.

25:29.903 --> 25:31.280
He got hurt
six months ago.

25:31.280 --> 25:32.865
He's deep
into an addiction,

25:32.865 --> 25:35.034
and he's walking around
with a loaded gun.

25:35.034 --> 25:36.285
And, sir,
i‐it's not just that.

25:36.285 --> 25:38.287
I‐I went back
to his hotel room.

25:38.287 --> 25:39.329
There were
prescription bottles

25:39.329 --> 25:40.873
with other people's names
on 'em.

25:40.873 --> 25:42.583
And he could be doing anything
to get those pills.

25:42.583 --> 25:44.460
Cops have to be held to
a higher standard.

25:44.460 --> 25:46.086
Anything less,
all hell breaks loose.

25:46.086 --> 25:48.464
I agree.

25:48.464 --> 25:51.467
I just wanted to make sure
you saw the repercussions.

25:51.467 --> 25:53.135
He's going to
lose his pension.

25:53.135 --> 25:55.637
Yeah.
I‐I struggled with that.

25:58.348 --> 26:00.559
But it's what I should have
done with Isabel.

26:00.559 --> 26:02.770
Alright.

26:02.770 --> 26:03.979
So, one more thing.

26:03.979 --> 26:06.106
Chen's going on
a special assignment today.

26:06.106 --> 26:09.151
She'll be joining Harper
on an undercover operation.

26:09.151 --> 26:12.237
This is Sergeant June Zhang
of Fresno PD.

26:12.237 --> 26:14.239
We are gonna help out
on her op today.

26:14.239 --> 26:16.075
Appreciate
the assistance, guys.

26:16.075 --> 26:17.743
I'm June, the UC.

26:17.743 --> 26:19.411
My case officer,
Lieutenant Balasco,

26:19.411 --> 26:22.247
who is not nearly as mean
and awful as he looks.

26:22.247 --> 26:23.582
[ Laughter ]
For the last eight months,

26:23.582 --> 26:26.210
I have been up on a crew
out of San Jose who made bank

26:26.210 --> 26:28.545
selling precursors of
liquid Fentanyl.

26:28.545 --> 26:30.923
But they got greedy, tried to go
from selling the parts

26:30.923 --> 26:33.300
to making and selling
the finished product.

26:33.300 --> 26:35.302
But their lab blew up,
killing their chemist

26:35.302 --> 26:36.887
and destroying
their entire supply,

26:36.887 --> 26:39.932
leaving them with no product
and a lot of pissed‐off buyers.

26:39.932 --> 26:42.559
Which is when I swooped in,
promising enough product

26:42.559 --> 26:44.686
to satisfy all their customers
and then some.

26:44.686 --> 26:47.564
But last night, all our
hard work almost fell apart,

26:47.564 --> 26:51.443
until the quick thinking
of Officer Chen saved my ass.

26:51.443 --> 26:53.112
Chen, stand up so they can
see what you're wearing.

26:53.112 --> 26:55.781
Yeah.
The op today is simple.

26:55.781 --> 26:58.408
Trade drugs for cash,
then arrest everybody

26:58.408 --> 27:01.370
and try to get them to flip on
Aldo Salonga, their boss.

27:01.370 --> 27:03.080
Alright.
You have your assignment.

27:03.080 --> 27:05.374
Everyone in position
by 10:00 a. m.

27:05.374 --> 27:07.584
[ Indistinct conversations ]

27:07.584 --> 27:08.794
What the hell
are you doing?

27:08.794 --> 27:10.671
You can't pit an
untrained probationary officer

27:10.671 --> 27:11.713
against one of
the most dangerous

27:11.713 --> 27:13.173
crime syndicates
in California.

27:13.173 --> 27:14.967
I don't want to hear it, Tim.
She volunteered.

27:14.967 --> 27:16.552
Plus, Grey authorized it,

27:16.552 --> 27:19.388
and we have some of
the best operational expertise

27:19.388 --> 27:20.556
she could ask for.

27:20.556 --> 27:23.183
They know the gladiator cage
you're walking into.

27:23.183 --> 27:25.185
You don't.
That's not volunteering.

27:25.185 --> 27:26.270
That's being used.

27:28.605 --> 27:31.733
Hey, don't let Bradford
kill your confidence, okay?

27:31.733 --> 27:35.487
His...hang‐ups about UC work
are his to deal with, not yours.

27:35.487 --> 27:37.906
I kinda hoped that
he would be proud of me.

27:37.906 --> 27:40.659
Wow. That sounds stupid
when I say it out loud.

27:40.659 --> 27:43.245
No, it doesn't.
He's your training officer.

27:43.245 --> 27:44.413
He's gotten you this far.

27:44.413 --> 27:46.540
There's nothing wrong
with wanting his approval.

27:46.540 --> 27:48.834
And for what it's worth,
you've got mine.

27:48.834 --> 27:51.336
You handled yourself
like a pro last night.

27:51.336 --> 27:52.588
Those instincts
can't be taught.

27:52.588 --> 27:54.339
Thanks.

27:54.339 --> 27:56.091
Hey!
I need your help!

27:56.091 --> 27:57.718
Somebody hurt Silas!
Come on!

27:57.718 --> 28:02.264
♪♪

28:02.264 --> 28:03.849
I came by this morning,
found him like this.

28:03.849 --> 28:06.226
He won't say
what happened.

28:06.226 --> 28:08.937
Silas.
Look, Officer West is here.

28:08.937 --> 28:12.649
Hey, Silas.
Looks like it hurts.

28:12.649 --> 28:16.069
Did you, uh,
crash your bike?

28:16.069 --> 28:18.947
Someone hurt you?

28:18.947 --> 28:20.657
Where is your bike?
It's okay.

28:20.657 --> 28:22.284
You can talk to us.

28:22.284 --> 28:24.828
If anything happened,
let us help.

28:24.828 --> 28:26.288
I called his mother.

28:26.288 --> 28:27.831
She's ‐‐ She's on her way
back from work now.

28:27.831 --> 28:30.042
Okay, well,
in the meantime, Silas,

28:30.042 --> 28:31.460
come back
to the Center,

28:31.460 --> 28:33.003
and we'll get those wounds
cleaned up, alright?

28:34.171 --> 28:36.006
I'm never
going back there.

28:36.006 --> 28:39.217
What? Why?

28:39.217 --> 28:42.638
Look, uh,
I'm sorry to hear that.

28:42.638 --> 28:44.264
Do you mind if I borrow
your notebook?

28:44.264 --> 28:48.101
Finish up
your patrol for you?

28:48.101 --> 28:49.436
Look, I'll, uh,
bring it back.

28:49.436 --> 28:50.729
Promise.

28:54.107 --> 28:56.360
Hey, can you, uh ‐‐
can you stay with him?

28:56.360 --> 28:58.195
Yeah.
[ Cellphone buttons beeping ]

28:58.195 --> 29:01.907
[ <i>Line ringing</i> ]
Hey. Yeah, it's, uh,
Jackson West.

29:01.907 --> 29:03.033
Are you still working
in the area?

29:03.033 --> 29:09.373
♪♪

29:09.373 --> 29:11.541
[ Car doors closing ]

29:11.541 --> 29:15.337
♪♪

29:15.337 --> 29:17.172
[ Click, radio beeps ]

29:17.172 --> 29:19.466
Control, 7‐Adam‐07,
show us Code 6.

29:19.466 --> 29:20.884
[ Radio beeps ]

29:20.884 --> 29:23.387
Silas' last entry was a broken
street light at this address.

29:23.387 --> 29:25.097
Something happened.
Check it out.

29:25.097 --> 29:29.893
♪♪

29:29.893 --> 29:34.731
♪♪

29:34.731 --> 29:36.191
The bike.

29:36.191 --> 29:41.154
♪♪

29:41.154 --> 29:43.365
[ Pounds on door ]
Police!

29:43.365 --> 29:45.575
<i>[ Cheers and applause</i>
<i>on television ]</i>

29:45.575 --> 29:47.494
What?
Sir, we need to
talk to you

29:47.494 --> 29:48.620
about this bike over here
and what happened

29:48.620 --> 29:50.038
to the young man
who was riding it.

29:50.038 --> 29:51.498
Bobby: <i>...Madness,"</i>

29:51.498 --> 29:52.374
<i>the show where</i>
<i>everyone's a winner.</i>

29:52.374 --> 29:53.375
Sir, open the door
right now.

29:54.376 --> 29:55.711
He's running!

29:55.711 --> 29:57.337
[ Door bangs ]

29:57.337 --> 29:58.755
<i>...and win the gold.</i>

29:58.755 --> 30:00.465
<i>Now here he is.</i>

30:00.465 --> 30:02.718
Nothing.
<i>[Speaking indistinctly]</i>
<i>with the gift of gab,</i>

30:02.718 --> 30:04.511
<i>your "Money Madness" host,</i>
<i>Sam Lovejoy.</i>

30:04.511 --> 30:06.680
Show yourself now!

30:06.680 --> 30:07.848
Lovejoy: <i>Thank you, Bobby,</i>
<i>and hello, everybody.</i>

30:07.848 --> 30:09.433
<i>This is "Money Madness."</i>

30:09.433 --> 30:11.560
<i>I'm Sam Lovejoy,</i>
<i>and I just can't wait</i>

30:11.560 --> 30:13.353
<i>to give away all this cash.</i>
<i>[ Cheers and applause ]</i>

30:13.353 --> 30:14.604
<i>Just look at my suit pocket.</i>

30:14.604 --> 30:16.565
<i>It's bursting at the seams</i>
<i>with cash.</i>

30:16.565 --> 30:19.276
<i>Now, Bobby, who's tonight's</i>
<i>first soon‐to‐be winner?</i>

30:19.276 --> 30:21.445
Bobby: <i>Sam, this is</i>
<i>Miss Donna McGee</i>

30:21.445 --> 30:23.572
<i>from Akron, Ohio.</i>
McGee: <i>Hello.</i>

30:23.572 --> 30:25.323
Lovejoy: <i>Now, Bobby, who do we</i>
<i>have playing on the phone?</i>

30:25.323 --> 30:26.491
Bobby: <i>Just darling Donna.</i>

30:26.491 --> 30:27.743
<i>[ Lovejoy speaking</i>
<i>indistinctly ]</i>

30:27.743 --> 30:28.744
Earl:
Get out of my house!

30:28.744 --> 30:30.328
[ Bang, objects clattering ]

30:30.328 --> 30:32.998
This is my house!
Get out of it, I said!

30:32.998 --> 30:34.541
Hey, hey!
Come on. Come on.

30:34.541 --> 30:36.126
Come on!

30:36.126 --> 30:38.045
[ Handcuffs click ]
[ Grunting ] Ow!

30:38.045 --> 30:40.338
He was spying on me!

30:40.338 --> 30:43.133
I saw him, outside,
writing things about me,

30:43.133 --> 30:44.468
saying I'm crazy.
I'm not crazy!

30:44.468 --> 30:45.594
He's just a kid.

30:45.594 --> 30:46.428
He was staring at
a broken street light.

30:46.428 --> 30:47.637
You didn't have to
hurt him.

30:47.637 --> 30:49.056
Liar.
Liar!

30:49.056 --> 30:50.682
I taught him.
I taught him.

30:50.682 --> 30:51.433
I taught him!

30:56.813 --> 30:59.149
[ Siren wailing in distance ]

30:59.149 --> 31:03.278
♪♪

31:03.278 --> 31:04.404
I know you're worried
about Lucy.

31:04.404 --> 31:05.947
Who said I was worried?

31:05.947 --> 31:08.408
I'm just saying,
she can handle herself.

31:08.408 --> 31:11.161
I <i>know</i> she can.
I trained her.

31:11.161 --> 31:13.371
[ Radio beeps ]
Eagle One in place.

31:13.371 --> 31:16.625
Alright, uh, let's go over this
one more time.

31:16.625 --> 31:18.668
Salonga's crew arrives,

31:18.668 --> 31:21.129
you test the Fentanyl,
give them a show,

31:21.129 --> 31:22.506
we get the money,
they get this van,

31:22.506 --> 31:24.841
and then, boom,
strike team takes them down.

31:24.841 --> 31:26.176
Walk in the park.

31:26.176 --> 31:28.011
And if not...

31:28.011 --> 31:29.596
[ Shotgun cocks ]

31:29.596 --> 31:31.598
...we make some noise until
the cavalry arrives.

31:33.433 --> 31:35.310
You want to go over
the signals again?

31:35.310 --> 31:37.604
Yeah. "Workhorse" means
we're in trouble.

31:37.604 --> 31:39.648
And "Beautiful day,"
we're all good.

31:39.648 --> 31:42.567
Lucy.
Mm‐hmm?

31:42.567 --> 31:44.820
Are <i>you</i> all good?
Yeah. Yes.

31:44.820 --> 31:47.364
You know, if you're not nervous,
you're not human.

31:47.364 --> 31:51.118
Okay? So, use this
to your advantage.

31:51.118 --> 31:54.329
Be scared. Be wild.
Be unpredictable.

31:54.329 --> 31:55.914
Be a cobra.

31:55.914 --> 31:57.249
[ Hisses ]

31:57.249 --> 31:59.584
[ Both laugh ]

32:01.503 --> 32:03.130
Can I ask you
a question?

32:03.130 --> 32:04.673
No.
What's your formula

32:04.673 --> 32:06.383
for when you tell people
you're a police officer

32:06.383 --> 32:07.551
in off‐duty life?

32:07.551 --> 32:09.928
I try not to put myself
in social situations

32:09.928 --> 32:11.596
where I need to.
Right.

32:11.596 --> 32:14.141
It's just that I got outed as
a cop in my Criminal Law class,

32:14.141 --> 32:15.225
and there's some
pretty strong feelings

32:15.225 --> 32:17.936
that I should've been
upfront about it.

32:17.936 --> 32:19.604
You did the right thing
keeping it a secret.

32:19.604 --> 32:20.897
Now you gotta
sit in the back row,

32:20.897 --> 32:22.315
always have your eyes
on the door.

32:22.315 --> 32:24.359
Why?

32:24.359 --> 32:25.777
Because they know
you're a cop now,

32:25.777 --> 32:27.279
which means they know you carry
an off‐duty weapon.

32:27.279 --> 32:28.780
Somebody may try
to take it from you,

32:28.780 --> 32:30.490
or maybe just attack you
because they hate cops.

32:30.490 --> 32:33.535
All due respect, I can't live
my life like that ‐‐

32:33.535 --> 32:35.036
with being suspicious
of people,

32:35.036 --> 32:36.997
seeing the world
as dangerous.

32:36.997 --> 32:39.374
The world <i>is</i> dangerous.

32:39.374 --> 32:40.959
Being vigilant is
the price of admission.

32:40.959 --> 32:45.422
♪♪

32:45.422 --> 32:46.715
[ Radio beeps ]
It's go time.

32:46.715 --> 32:52.596
♪♪

32:52.596 --> 32:54.639
Let's do this!
Where's the money?

32:54.639 --> 32:56.057
First things first.

32:56.057 --> 32:57.642
I wanna test
the shipment.

32:57.642 --> 33:01.021
♪♪

33:01.021 --> 33:02.856
[ Door opens ]

33:02.856 --> 33:11.198
♪♪

33:11.198 --> 33:19.789
♪♪

33:19.789 --> 33:28.632
♪♪

33:28.632 --> 33:36.431
♪♪

33:36.431 --> 33:38.850
Hard positives
on every scale.

33:38.850 --> 33:40.018
When's the last time
you saw that?

33:40.018 --> 33:41.519
Never.

33:41.519 --> 33:42.938
There's nothing available
this pure.

33:42.938 --> 33:45.065
Now let's see
the cash.

33:46.107 --> 33:48.026
[ Radio clicks ]
We're in business.

33:48.026 --> 33:49.444
♪♪

33:49.444 --> 33:50.362
[ Vehicle approaching ]

33:50.362 --> 33:51.905
Nolan:
Who the hell is that?

33:51.905 --> 33:53.448
[ Radio beeps ]
We've got another guest
at the party.

33:53.448 --> 33:54.699
Standby for rescue.

33:54.699 --> 33:56.284
If this is a set‐up,
you're the first to go.

33:56.284 --> 33:58.828
Relax.

33:58.828 --> 34:00.080
It's just my boss.

34:01.998 --> 34:05.126
And he wants
to talk...to you.

34:05.126 --> 34:06.962
Me?
[ Window motor whirs ]

34:08.964 --> 34:10.048
Good morning.

34:11.800 --> 34:13.426
My apologies
for last night.

34:13.426 --> 34:15.887
Sato overstepped.

34:15.887 --> 34:16.972
It won't happen again.

34:19.557 --> 34:20.976
Come in and talk to me.

34:20.976 --> 34:23.311
Why?
[ Chuckles ]

34:23.311 --> 34:26.439
A monkey can be taught
to test for drugs...

34:26.439 --> 34:29.442
or a cop.

34:29.442 --> 34:32.737
I need to see that
you really know the science.

34:32.737 --> 34:34.906
Why aren't we going in there
and arresting everybody?

34:34.906 --> 34:36.157
We need to see
the money first.

34:36.157 --> 34:37.826
[ Inhales sharply ]

34:41.037 --> 34:43.707
What the hell.
It's a beautiful day.

34:43.707 --> 34:45.375
Nothing's gonna go wrong.

34:45.375 --> 34:52.340
♪♪

34:52.340 --> 34:54.134
Don't concern yourself
with him.

34:54.134 --> 34:56.261
It's a little hard
not to.

34:56.261 --> 34:58.221
[ Car door locks ]

34:58.221 --> 34:59.389
Okay, stop trying
to scare me

34:59.389 --> 35:00.682
and just tell me
what we're doing here.

35:00.682 --> 35:03.560
Simple.

35:03.560 --> 35:06.855
I know
a little chemistry.

35:06.855 --> 35:11.109
The hydromorphone hydrochloride
you're selling ‐‐

35:11.109 --> 35:12.360
remind me
of the formula.

35:17.365 --> 35:20.619
[ Speaking Tagalog ]

35:20.619 --> 35:23.163
[ Speaking Tagalog ]

35:34.215 --> 35:36.468
You speak Tagalog.

35:36.468 --> 35:39.304
My best friend in elementary
school grew up in Quezon City.

35:39.304 --> 35:42.515
I...basically
lived at her house.

35:42.515 --> 35:44.351
I picked up a little bit.

35:44.351 --> 35:47.270
[ Marker scribbling ]

35:47.270 --> 35:48.521
Problem?

35:48.521 --> 35:51.191
Nope.

35:51.191 --> 35:54.319
I just have a flair
for the dramatic.

35:54.319 --> 35:57.072
Okay.
Are we done?

35:57.072 --> 35:59.824
I like you.

35:59.824 --> 36:01.618
So I have an offer.

36:01.618 --> 36:04.120
I kill Coco
and the other one.

36:04.120 --> 36:07.040
You keep
half the money.

36:07.040 --> 36:08.041
Come work for me.

36:10.877 --> 36:13.046
[ Exhales sharply ]

36:13.046 --> 36:15.340
Betrayal's not really
my style,

36:15.340 --> 36:17.258
but I'm flattered
by the offer.

36:17.258 --> 36:18.968
Can we finish the deal now?

36:18.968 --> 36:21.137
[ Exhales sharply ]

36:24.516 --> 36:26.518
[ Car door unlocks ]

36:26.518 --> 36:34.567
♪♪

36:34.567 --> 36:42.325
♪♪

36:42.325 --> 36:50.083
♪♪

36:50.083 --> 36:52.460
Now, that's sexy.

36:52.460 --> 36:54.879
[ Tires squealing,
vehicles approaching ]

36:54.879 --> 36:56.381
[ Sirens wailing ]

36:56.381 --> 36:58.883
♪♪

36:58.883 --> 37:00.218
Weapons down!

37:00.218 --> 37:01.511
Weapons down on the ground
right now!

37:01.511 --> 37:03.012
Drop the gun!
Hands above your head!

37:03.012 --> 37:04.389
Interlace your fingers!

37:04.389 --> 37:06.015
Put your hands behind your head!
Interlace your fingers now!

37:06.015 --> 37:07.600
Hands behind your head.

37:07.600 --> 37:09.018
[ Handcuffs click ]
Man: Hands up, weapons down.

37:09.018 --> 37:11.062
Do <i>not</i> move.
You okay?

37:11.062 --> 37:13.148
Give me your hands.
Sato!

37:13.148 --> 37:14.733
You set us up,
you snitch!

37:14.733 --> 37:16.276
You're dead!
You hear me?!

37:16.276 --> 37:17.736
‐Eyes on him.
‐You're dead!

37:17.736 --> 37:21.156
You watch your back!
This brings back
some memories.

37:21.156 --> 37:24.701
First day together.
Oh, right.

37:24.701 --> 37:26.035
Watch your head.

37:26.035 --> 37:32.000
♪♪

37:32.000 --> 37:34.544
[ Police radio chatter ]

37:34.544 --> 37:36.629
You did good.

37:36.629 --> 37:44.262
♪♪

37:49.684 --> 37:52.061
Beth. Hey.

37:52.061 --> 37:53.313
You okay?

37:53.313 --> 37:57.150
Tim Bradford,
my hero and savior.

37:57.150 --> 37:58.276
I didn't
have a choice.

37:58.276 --> 37:59.694
The hell you didn't.

37:59.694 --> 38:01.362
When your coked out ex‐wife
was working undercover,

38:01.362 --> 38:02.947
you had all kinds
of options.

38:02.947 --> 38:06.534
Now, all of a sudden,
your hands are tied?

38:06.534 --> 38:09.287
Hypocritical bastard.

38:09.287 --> 38:11.790
I‐I can't excuse
the past, okay?

38:11.790 --> 38:13.041
But this is now,

38:13.041 --> 38:14.626
and Mack crossed
too many lines.

38:14.626 --> 38:17.504
I have three young kids
and a husband

38:17.504 --> 38:19.714
who is looking
at <i>years</i> in state prison

38:19.714 --> 38:21.508
and no more pension.

38:21.508 --> 38:24.844
How am I supposed to
feed my kids?

38:24.844 --> 38:27.680
I'm sorry this happened.

38:27.680 --> 38:29.808
But I didn't do it to you.

38:29.808 --> 38:30.850
Mack did.

38:30.850 --> 38:34.270
You...are a cop.

38:34.270 --> 38:36.439
You're supposed to
look out for your own.

38:36.439 --> 38:40.068
♪♪

38:40.068 --> 38:43.363
♪ I wasn't the favorite ♪

38:43.363 --> 38:46.115
♪ I wasn't the first one
off the gun ♪

38:46.115 --> 38:49.994
[ Grunts ]
♪ Might have seemed
I was chasing ♪

38:49.994 --> 38:51.246
Hey.

38:51.246 --> 38:53.248
[ Chuckles ]
You gotta be kidding me.

38:53.248 --> 38:55.750
[ Scoffs ]
What's so funny?

38:55.750 --> 38:58.253
♪ No, never count me out ♪

38:58.253 --> 38:59.796
♪ No, it ain't how you start ♪

38:59.796 --> 39:01.881
Wow.
[ Chuckles ]

39:01.881 --> 39:03.508
So, what do we do now?

39:03.508 --> 39:05.301
Let the kid choose.

39:05.301 --> 39:06.219
You know he's gonna
choose mine, right?

39:06.219 --> 39:08.054
[ Chuckles ]
You wanna put money on that?

39:08.054 --> 39:09.222
How about dinner?

39:09.222 --> 39:12.350
I don't know,
I heard you had a boyfriend.

39:12.350 --> 39:13.518
Hmm.
The actor?

39:13.518 --> 39:15.228
[ Laughs ] Doing a little
background on me, huh?

39:17.188 --> 39:19.607
Well, that boyfriend
is no more.

39:19.607 --> 39:21.734
Long story.

39:21.734 --> 39:23.695
I look forward to hearing
about it over dinner.

39:23.695 --> 39:28.074
♪ How you finish,
finish, finish ♪

39:28.074 --> 39:30.201
♪ Ain't saying it's easy ♪

39:30.201 --> 39:32.871
You know we don't have class
tonight, right?

39:32.871 --> 39:35.331
Right. I‐I just ‐‐
I needed some help.

39:35.331 --> 39:37.250
I'm not gonna write
your paper for you.

39:37.250 --> 39:40.920
No. No. I‐I was hoping maybe you
could tell me <i>what</i> to write.

39:40.920 --> 39:42.630
I've spent the last two days
talking to cops about

39:42.630 --> 39:44.257
whether I should've
identified myself,

39:44.257 --> 39:47.552
and the answers have ranged from
"probably not" to "no way."

39:47.552 --> 39:50.597
But...I am struggling

39:50.597 --> 39:53.308
with how betrayed
my classmates felt.

39:53.308 --> 39:57.604
So, I just...need a little
outside perspective.

39:57.604 --> 40:00.607
You should've
said something.

40:00.607 --> 40:02.942
I'm sure there are
a dozen reasons why cops think

40:02.942 --> 40:04.611
that your job is
a need‐to‐know thing,

40:04.611 --> 40:05.737
but come on.

40:05.737 --> 40:07.363
It's 2021.

40:07.363 --> 40:09.949
You guys have a hell of a lot
to make up for.

40:09.949 --> 40:12.410
So, you want to
win back trust?

40:12.410 --> 40:14.495
You gotta assume a higher level
of responsibility.

40:14.495 --> 40:17.790
You gotta go the extra mile
every single time.

40:17.790 --> 40:20.084
You think I have a chance
to mend some fences here?

40:20.084 --> 40:23.212
Yeah. I do.

40:23.212 --> 40:25.715
Everyone in this classroom
wants to change the system,

40:25.715 --> 40:29.802
and they're driven by hope
and a ton of anger.

40:29.802 --> 40:32.847
But hope is what keeps them
moving forward.

40:32.847 --> 40:34.182
So if they see that
you're serious

40:34.182 --> 40:35.934
about being part of
the change,

40:35.934 --> 40:38.645
they'll let you back in.

40:38.645 --> 40:40.521
Thank you.
Mm‐hmm.

40:40.521 --> 40:41.898
♪ The beginning ♪

40:41.898 --> 40:43.191
That's so ‐‐ I ‐‐

40:43.191 --> 40:44.317
I should've
written that down.

40:44.317 --> 40:45.526
What was the part
in the beginning,

40:45.526 --> 40:47.278
when you said that...

40:47.278 --> 40:48.446
You know what?
I ‐‐ I got it.

40:48.446 --> 40:50.698
It's ‐‐ Thank you very much.
It's good stuff.

40:50.698 --> 40:52.742
[ Laughter ]

40:52.742 --> 40:55.536
Oh, and they always want us
to go undercover as strippers.

40:55.536 --> 40:56.704
Harper: Yes!

40:56.704 --> 40:58.831
As if our bodies are
the only thing we have.

40:58.831 --> 41:00.291
[ Laughing ] Yes.
Well, actually,

41:00.291 --> 41:02.961
my ‐‐ my body does have
magical powers,

41:02.961 --> 41:05.964
<i>but</i> it does,
a lot of the times,

41:05.964 --> 41:09.676
feel like, as a female UC,
that they just want to

41:09.676 --> 41:12.428
get you naked
for the guys in the van.

41:12.428 --> 41:14.639
Mm‐hmm, so that they can
drool over you

41:14.639 --> 41:17.350
in a cloud of their own farts.
[ Laughs ]

41:17.350 --> 41:19.519
I don't think I can use
any of this for my paper.

41:19.519 --> 41:20.687
Okay. Alright.

41:20.687 --> 41:22.563
What ‐‐ What exactly
do you need to know?

41:22.563 --> 41:25.441
Women have been cops

41:25.441 --> 41:28.111
in the LAPD
over 100 years now,

41:28.111 --> 41:30.113
but does it still feel like
you have to act like a man

41:30.113 --> 41:32.115
to fit in?
Good question.

41:32.115 --> 41:34.450
Well, you're the rookie,
the last one in.

41:34.450 --> 41:35.785
What do you think?

41:35.785 --> 41:37.912
Um...

41:37.912 --> 41:40.456
Mm, I think...

41:40.456 --> 41:42.834
I think fitting in
is a trap.

41:42.834 --> 41:46.671
I'm sitting between two of
the best cops in the state...

41:46.671 --> 41:49.090
Mm.
...who had to navigate

41:49.090 --> 41:53.011
an avalanche of obstacles
just to get to the mountaintop.

41:53.011 --> 41:54.554
They didn't do it
by trying to fit in.

41:54.554 --> 41:57.348
They did it by ‐‐
you know, by, um...

41:57.348 --> 42:01.644
being stronger, smarter,
more agile.

42:01.644 --> 42:04.522
They had to to navigate
a system that still believes

42:04.522 --> 42:07.316
being a girl is inherently
soft or weak,

42:07.316 --> 42:10.486
as though empathy
is somehow a liability.

42:10.486 --> 42:12.780
There isn't a guy
in the force

42:12.780 --> 42:15.408
who can do what these guys
can do.
Mm.

42:15.408 --> 42:17.535
And there sure as hell
isn't anyone tougher.

42:17.535 --> 42:19.037
Hoo!
I will drink to that.

42:19.037 --> 42:20.038
Hell yeah.
[ Laughs ]

42:20.038 --> 42:21.914
[ Glasses clink ]

42:28.838 --> 42:37.221
♪♪

42:37.221 --> 42:45.438
♪♪

42:45.438 --> 42:53.946
♪♪

42:57.241 --> 42:58.951
[ Pencil scratching ]
Damn it!
